WEBVTT

00:06.840 --> 00:09.760
<i>[intense music]</i>

00:09.760 --> 00:16.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:16.016 --> 00:18.602
<i>- My name is John Clark,</i>
<i>and I'm from Portal, Georgia.</i>

00:18.602 --> 00:21.063
I am a full-time
police officer

00:21.063 --> 00:23.065
and a part-time bladesmith.

00:23.065 --> 00:24.691
<i>Coming out on top,</i>

00:24.691 --> 00:27.694
it would make me complete
as a bladesmith.

00:27.694 --> 00:31.156
<i>Definitely be on</i>
<i>the professional level.</i>

00:31.156 --> 00:33.659
<i>- My name is Atsatsa Antonio,</i>
<i>I'm 23 years old,</i>

00:33.659 --> 00:35.786
and I've been bladesmithing
for ten years.

00:35.786 --> 00:38.830
<i>My cultural heritage</i>
<i>plays a really big part</i>

00:38.830 --> 00:41.833
in the hows and whys
of what I do.

00:41.833 --> 00:44.294
<i>I'm doing this competition</i>
<i>because I want to be</i>

00:44.294 --> 00:48.298
the first Native American
"Forged in Fire" champion.

00:48.298 --> 00:51.176
<i>- My name is Bob Andrews,</i>
<i>and I'm from Challis, Idaho.</i>

00:51.176 --> 00:54.179
I'm an ornamental blacksmith,
full-time, for 30 years.

00:54.179 --> 00:58.141
I've made gates,
fire screens, furniture,

00:58.141 --> 01:00.477
<i>but I'm getting to the point</i>

01:00.477 --> 01:02.562
where I can't handle
the big projects anymore,

01:02.562 --> 01:05.774
<i>so I'm making more knives.</i>

01:05.774 --> 01:07.859
<i>- My name is Derek Melton.</i>

01:07.859 --> 01:09.861
<i>The thing I love the most</i>
<i>about bladesmithing</i>

01:09.861 --> 01:12.364
is the stress relief
and the creative outlet

01:12.364 --> 01:14.116
that I get.

01:14.116 --> 01:16.535
<i>My professional job</i>
<i>is as an IT Analyst</i>

01:16.535 --> 01:18.245
<i>for a large hospital,</i>

01:18.245 --> 01:20.706
and it's difficult
to manage stress,

01:20.706 --> 01:22.499
<i>so it's nice</i>
<i>at the end of the day</i>

01:22.499 --> 01:23.917
<i>to be able to come out</i>
<i>and smash something</i>

01:23.917 --> 01:26.086
with a hammer.

01:26.086 --> 01:28.797
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:28.797 --> 01:30.674
You're all here
to compete for the title

01:30.674 --> 01:32.926
of "Forged in Fire" champion
in three timed rounds

01:32.926 --> 01:35.137
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:35.137 --> 01:37.389
designed to push
every aspect of your skills

01:37.389 --> 01:39.725
in front of a panel
of expert judges who determines

01:39.725 --> 01:42.644
which of you will leave here
with that $10,000 check,

01:42.644 --> 01:44.354
so let's go ahead
and meet them now.

01:44.354 --> 01:47.399
Up first, ABS mastersmith
J. Neilson.

01:47.399 --> 01:49.401
Next, historic weapons
recreation specialist

01:49.401 --> 01:50.986
David Baker.

01:50.986 --> 01:52.404
And last,
edged weapon specialist

01:52.404 --> 01:55.032
Doug Marcaida.

01:55.032 --> 01:57.034
All right, let's dive right in.

01:57.034 --> 01:58.952
On your anvils there's a cloth.
Go ahead and lift that up.

01:58.952 --> 02:00.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:00.996 --> 02:05.500
That is a piece of pristine
5160 spring steel.

02:05.500 --> 02:07.961
You're probably thinking,
"That's plenty of steel that

02:07.961 --> 02:10.047
I can make a signature blade
in my signature style."

02:10.047 --> 02:12.799
However,
I don't want to see that.

02:12.799 --> 02:14.593
Today,
you'll be making a blade

02:14.593 --> 02:17.095
that's clean
and that requires precision.

02:18.388 --> 02:20.724
Today, you'll be forging
friction folders.

02:20.724 --> 02:22.726
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:22.726 --> 02:25.103
<i>Friction folders</i>
<i>have existed for centuries</i>

02:25.103 --> 02:27.481
<i>with the earliest forms</i>
<i>dating back to ancient Rome.</i>

02:27.481 --> 02:29.733
<i>Over the years,</i>

02:29.733 --> 02:31.902
<i>friction folders have taken on</i>
<i>various shapes and forms,</i>

02:31.902 --> 02:34.196
<i>but the key element</i>
<i>remains the same.</i>

02:34.196 --> 02:36.823
<i>The blade stays open</i>
<i>or closed by friction only,</i>

02:36.823 --> 02:39.660
<i>with no other locking system</i>
<i>in place.</i>

02:39.660 --> 02:42.579
<i>- Oh, God,</i>
<i>it couldn't have been easy.</i>

02:42.579 --> 02:44.623
Here I am thinking that

02:44.623 --> 02:46.958
I'm supposed to make
a fixed blade,

02:46.958 --> 02:49.753
<i>and he drops</i>
<i>the bombshell on us.</i>

02:49.753 --> 02:51.421
<i>- In the second round,</i>

02:51.421 --> 02:53.298
<i>you'll attach handles</i>
<i>to those blades,</i>

02:53.298 --> 02:55.258
<i>turning them into fully</i>
<i>functional friction folders,</i>

02:55.258 --> 02:57.052
but I'm not gonna tell you
what the tests are

02:57.052 --> 02:58.679
because I don't want to see

02:58.679 --> 03:00.472
a hunk of steel
with just an edge on it

03:00.472 --> 03:03.475
meant to blast
through a target.

03:03.475 --> 03:05.977
You'll have to design
and forge your friction folders

03:05.977 --> 03:07.270
in three hours.

03:07.270 --> 03:08.897
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:08.897 --> 03:11.191
Your three hours starts...

03:11.191 --> 03:12.442
now.

03:12.442 --> 03:16.530
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:16.530 --> 03:18.156
<i>- What do you guys think</i>
<i>of this challenge?</i>

03:18.156 --> 03:19.783
- It's not easy.

03:19.783 --> 03:21.451
You gotta get
your pin placement right.

03:21.451 --> 03:24.121
It's got to sit center;
it's got to stay closed

03:24.121 --> 03:26.164
and open on its own
without assistance.

03:26.164 --> 03:28.166
It's a tricky test.
- Yeah.

03:28.166 --> 03:29.835
<i>- I have the least amount</i>
<i>of experience</i>

03:29.835 --> 03:31.503
<i>than all the other guys.</i>

03:31.503 --> 03:33.839
<i>I just hope</i>
<i>that what I produce</i>

03:33.839 --> 03:36.341
can stand up to par
with what they produce.

03:36.341 --> 03:38.385
<i>This is a huge piece of steel,</i>

03:38.385 --> 03:41.930
and I gotta get this coil
uncoiled.

03:41.930 --> 03:43.932
- That is tempered material.

03:43.932 --> 03:47.102
You're going to have to get
that very hot to uncoil it.

03:47.102 --> 03:49.604
<i>- This is already</i>
<i>a dangerous option</i>

03:49.604 --> 03:51.690
<i>on how I'm choosing</i>
<i>to do this,</i>

03:51.690 --> 03:54.151
<i>and now it's becoming</i>
<i>all the more dangerous</i>

03:54.151 --> 03:57.028
because the steel is
still slipping inside the vice.

03:57.028 --> 04:01.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:01.408 --> 04:02.659
- Uh-oh.

04:02.659 --> 04:04.077
- These coils are tricky.

04:04.077 --> 04:06.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:06.830 --> 04:08.790
- Because I don't know
the test

04:08.790 --> 04:11.042
that this knife
is gonna have to pass,

04:11.042 --> 04:15.589
<i>I need to think about a blade</i>
<i>that will perform adequately</i>

04:15.589 --> 04:18.008
<i>in a number</i>
<i>of different tasks.</i>

04:18.008 --> 04:20.343
- We know how precise

04:20.343 --> 04:22.471
those measurements
and grinds need to be

04:22.471 --> 04:24.890
in order for those folders
to operate correctly.

04:24.890 --> 04:27.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:27.392 --> 04:29.770
<i>- I feel confident</i>
<i>that I can get this job done</i>

04:29.770 --> 04:31.563
if I manage my time right.

04:31.563 --> 04:33.440
<i>I have the coil spring open</i>

04:33.440 --> 04:35.484
<i>and in a fairly straight bar.</i>

04:35.484 --> 04:38.236
<i>My next move is, start</i>
<i>turning this into bar stock.</i>

04:38.236 --> 04:42.616
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:42.616 --> 04:43.909
- I've never made
a friction folder.

04:43.909 --> 04:45.160
That's what's the challenge.

04:45.160 --> 04:47.120
Got hot spots.

04:47.120 --> 04:48.830
- I think I'm gonna
have to go to big blue.

04:48.830 --> 04:51.208
- Bob and Derek have
this real nice thing set up.

04:51.208 --> 04:52.793
Bob goes to the press,

04:52.793 --> 04:55.045
turns it on, works,
calls out when he's done,

04:55.045 --> 04:57.005
and Derek goes
right in behind him.

04:57.005 --> 04:58.757
- It's a competition,

04:58.757 --> 05:01.510
and only one person
takes home the title

05:01.510 --> 05:03.094
<i>of "Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

05:03.094 --> 05:05.514
<i>but that doesn't mean</i>
<i>you can't help.</i>

05:05.514 --> 05:07.516
I'm competing against myself.

05:07.516 --> 05:09.976
<i>It's not the three guys.</i>

05:09.976 --> 05:12.437
<i>Basically, my game plan is get</i>
<i>the steel hot and hit it hard.</i>

05:12.437 --> 05:13.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:13.897 --> 05:16.316
<i>I'll figure it out as I go.</i>

05:16.316 --> 05:19.152
- My background,
I'm Navajo and Shawnee,

05:19.152 --> 05:21.905
<i>and for us, steel itself</i>
<i>has a spirit within.</i>

05:21.905 --> 05:23.532
And so when
you're working with it,

05:23.532 --> 05:25.492
you have to really communicate
with that spirit.

05:25.492 --> 05:27.327
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:27.327 --> 05:29.412
<i>These springs</i>
<i>are super hard to uncoil.</i>

05:29.412 --> 05:31.873
<i>The only way I'm going to get</i>
<i>this spring uncoiled</i>

05:31.873 --> 05:33.416
<i>is to cut it.</i>

05:33.416 --> 05:35.627
- Now, Atsatsa's
got the right idea.

05:35.627 --> 05:37.295
Lose half of it.
both: Yeah.

05:37.295 --> 05:39.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:39.756 --> 05:41.800
<i>- A friction folder</i>
<i>is a knife</i>

05:41.800 --> 05:44.302
that has a lot
of mechanical aspects to it.

05:44.302 --> 05:47.347
<i>The tricky part is you have</i>
<i>to create a pivot point.</i>

05:47.347 --> 05:50.559
<i>That way, it will fold out</i>
<i>and fold in evenly</i>

05:50.559 --> 05:52.227
without any breaks or gaps.

05:52.227 --> 05:54.062
<i>For someone like me</i>

05:54.062 --> 05:56.481
<i>who has just made</i>
<i>fixed blade knives,</i>

05:56.481 --> 05:58.692
<i>making a friction folder is...</i>

05:58.692 --> 06:01.444
one of the worst scenarios
that you can be thrown into.

06:01.444 --> 06:04.030
<i>- Look, if you've never made</i>
<i>a friction folder before,</i>

06:04.030 --> 06:06.324
<i>it is going to be difficult</i>
<i>to figure out accurately</i>

06:06.324 --> 06:08.034
<i>how to make that mechanism,</i>

06:08.034 --> 06:10.078
<i>especially</i>
<i>in a timed challenge.</i>

06:10.078 --> 06:12.664
<i>- I finally have</i>
<i>a workable bar of steel.</i>

06:12.664 --> 06:15.584
I just go to town,
just starting to forge out

06:15.584 --> 06:17.502
<i>what I have in my mind</i>
<i>is going to be the blade</i>

06:17.502 --> 06:19.880
<i>that I'm going to make.</i>

06:19.880 --> 06:21.840
- Bladesmiths,
you have two hours remaining

06:21.840 --> 06:23.008
to finish your work.

06:23.008 --> 06:25.594
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:25.594 --> 06:27.846
- Come on,
let's move some steel.

06:27.846 --> 06:30.432
I like Bob--
I like the way Bob's hammering.

06:30.432 --> 06:34.936
- I'm designing this blade
as I go with every hammer blow

06:34.936 --> 06:36.897
and how
it's going to fit together.

06:36.897 --> 06:40.233
<i>My thought process</i>
<i>on having my tail</i>

06:40.233 --> 06:42.027
<i>a little bit higher</i>
<i>than my spine</i>

06:42.027 --> 06:45.363
is so that when
the friction folder is open,

06:45.363 --> 06:47.073
you kind of have a guard.

06:47.073 --> 06:50.327
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:50.327 --> 06:52.871
- My plan is to draw out
the material

06:52.871 --> 06:55.081
<i>and get it</i>
<i>to an even thickness</i>

06:55.081 --> 06:58.043
<i>with no bumps, no curves,</i>
<i>just a straight bar.</i>

06:58.043 --> 06:59.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:59.336 --> 07:01.338
<i>I draw the material out,</i>

07:01.338 --> 07:05.550
<i>and I start to visualize</i>
<i>how this knife is going to be.</i>

07:05.550 --> 07:08.470
At this point,
the knife is revealing itself.

07:08.470 --> 07:10.221
<i>Then I start</i>
<i>shaping the blade.</i>

07:10.221 --> 07:12.432
- Looks like Atsatsa
is gonna make us a very thin,

07:12.432 --> 07:14.768
very shallow blade.

07:14.768 --> 07:16.686
If you've seen
some of the tests we do,

07:16.686 --> 07:18.772
you would think you would
wanna fuller that blade out,

07:18.772 --> 07:20.523
get some size into it.

07:20.523 --> 07:21.941
We don't play games
with these tests.

07:21.941 --> 07:24.361
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:24.361 --> 07:27.280
<i>- I've got to focus</i>
<i>on that pivot point</i>

07:27.280 --> 07:29.824
<i>and how the handle material</i>

07:29.824 --> 07:33.036
and the tang and the tab
on the end of the tang

07:33.036 --> 07:34.746
are all gonna work together.

07:34.746 --> 07:37.123
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:37.123 --> 07:39.542
<i>- I'm able to get</i>
<i>the steel forged out</i>

07:39.542 --> 07:41.336
<i>into the billet</i>
<i>that I've been wanting.</i>

07:41.336 --> 07:43.129
I need to figure
out where

07:43.129 --> 07:45.215
I'm gonna stick the hole at
for the pivot point.

07:45.215 --> 07:47.467
<i>It's gotta be even,</i>
<i>it's gotta be precise.</i>

07:47.467 --> 07:50.011
<i>That way, it will fold out</i>
<i>and fold in evenly</i>

07:50.011 --> 07:51.805
<i>without any breaks or gaps.</i>

07:51.805 --> 07:53.848
- Two hours has elapsed!

07:53.848 --> 07:56.351
That gives you just
60 minutes remaining

07:56.351 --> 07:57.727
to finish your blades.

07:57.727 --> 07:59.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:59.521 --> 08:01.231
<i>- Even though</i>
<i>I see all the other guys</i>

08:01.231 --> 08:03.400
<i>are still</i>
<i>forging their blades,</i>

08:03.400 --> 08:05.360
I'm done forging.

08:05.360 --> 08:07.112
<i>I'm gonna go to the grinder,</i>

08:07.112 --> 08:09.114
<i>and I'm gonna</i>
<i>get my profiling done.</i>

08:09.114 --> 08:11.032
Without knowing what they're
gonna do at the testing,

08:11.032 --> 08:13.201
<i>I don't know what kind</i>
<i>of an edge we're gonna need,</i>

08:13.201 --> 08:15.203
whether they're gonna have
a shaving demonstration,

08:15.203 --> 08:17.205
uh...
or, you know,

08:17.205 --> 08:19.040
<i>they're gonna cut something</i>
<i>that's really tough,</i>

08:19.040 --> 08:21.668
<i>so you need to cover</i>
<i>every base there is.</i>

08:21.668 --> 08:23.878
- Bob's getting his blade
nice and flat.

08:23.878 --> 08:25.922
That way, when you put
that pin through 90 degrees,

08:25.922 --> 08:29.509
everything sets evenly.

08:29.509 --> 08:31.428
- The hardest thing
about making a friction folder

08:31.428 --> 08:34.222
is the little joint
of the knife, the folding part.

08:34.222 --> 08:35.932
<i>Right now,</i>
<i>I'm mainly afraid of the area</i>

08:35.932 --> 08:38.810
<i>where the tang starts.</i>

08:38.810 --> 08:41.020
- That ricasso
needs to be flat,

08:41.020 --> 08:43.273
as in both sides parallel.

08:43.273 --> 08:46.317
So if the ricasso
gets wide or flares

08:46.317 --> 08:48.111
as it gets closer
to the blade,

08:48.111 --> 08:49.904
that's gonna
throw off the scales,

08:49.904 --> 08:51.948
and that could effect
the way that the blade

08:51.948 --> 08:54.659
sits in that
friction folder handle.

08:54.659 --> 08:56.911
- Yep.

08:56.911 --> 08:58.913
<i>- My original design</i>
<i>that I drew out</i>

08:58.913 --> 09:01.249
<i>was a straight blade,</i>
<i>straight tang,</i>

09:01.249 --> 09:03.334
<i>and as I went</i>
<i>through the forging,</i>

09:03.334 --> 09:06.046
I just had a natural curve,
and I kind of looked at it

09:06.046 --> 09:07.922
and thought,
"Hey, that would be nice."

09:07.922 --> 09:10.091
There we go.

09:10.091 --> 09:13.344
<i>I get a glance over at</i>
<i>the other contestants' blades,</i>

09:13.344 --> 09:15.055
and they're all straight,

09:15.055 --> 09:17.474
<i>and I'm the only one</i>
<i>that has a curve to it.</i>

09:17.474 --> 09:24.731
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:24.731 --> 09:29.611
- It's time to quench,
and if this blade warps on me,

09:29.611 --> 09:31.946
<i>the warp</i>
<i>is not going to allow</i>

09:31.946 --> 09:34.824
for that blade to sit
inside a friction folder,

09:34.824 --> 09:36.785
and that would send me home.

09:36.785 --> 09:42.749
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:43.958 --> 09:45.460
- Oh!

09:45.460 --> 09:46.920
I think John
just lost his blade

09:46.920 --> 09:48.505
in the bottom of the oil.

09:48.505 --> 09:50.173
- My blade,
it could have a chip,

09:50.173 --> 09:52.008
it could have a crack,
it could have a warp.

09:52.008 --> 09:54.260
It could even be broken,
for all I know.

09:54.260 --> 09:57.472
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:57.472 --> 10:00.183
<i>- I could feel the blade</i>
<i>with the tongs,</i>

10:00.183 --> 10:02.644
<i>but I could not get</i>
<i>a good grip on it.</i>

10:02.644 --> 10:04.938
<i>I decided</i>
<i>I might as well just grab it.</i>

10:04.938 --> 10:07.899
This has got to be
a stupid idea.

10:07.899 --> 10:09.526
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:09.526 --> 10:12.237
I have just placed
a piece of metal

10:12.237 --> 10:16.866
that was at about 2,200 degrees
into this vat of oil.

10:16.866 --> 10:18.993
- Prepping his arm
for the dunk.

10:18.993 --> 10:21.329
<i>- Now, I'm having to reach</i>
<i>into the bottom of it</i>

10:21.329 --> 10:23.081
<i>to pull it out.</i>

10:23.081 --> 10:24.833
- Are we gonna see
some deep-fried arm?

10:24.833 --> 10:28.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:28.670 --> 10:30.046
- You got it, John!

10:30.046 --> 10:31.923
- There we go.

10:31.923 --> 10:34.509
- I am ecstatic.

10:34.509 --> 10:38.888
<i>No warps, no cracks,</i>
<i>and no chips.</i>

10:38.888 --> 10:40.598
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:40.598 --> 10:42.433
Oh, thank God.

10:42.433 --> 10:43.852
It's hard.

10:43.852 --> 10:47.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:47.230 --> 10:50.483
- Look at the size of the tail
that Bob is putting on there.

10:50.483 --> 10:54.529
The only concern I have is,
as that knife pivots,

10:54.529 --> 10:56.906
it's gonna have to have
a lot of room in that handle

10:56.906 --> 10:59.159
for the tail
to slide into.

10:59.159 --> 11:01.828
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:01.828 --> 11:04.164
- All right,
so Bob is in the oil.

11:04.164 --> 11:05.415
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:05.415 --> 11:07.167
<i>- The quench is critical,</i>

11:07.167 --> 11:09.085
<i>because if you don't</i>
<i>get the knife hard,</i>

11:09.085 --> 11:10.753
it'll never hold an edge.

11:10.753 --> 11:12.088
<i>Testing it with a file</i>

11:12.088 --> 11:13.506
<i>to make sure that I'm hard.</i>

11:13.506 --> 11:15.633
<i>I feel better now</i>

11:15.633 --> 11:20.346
than sitting down
to an Idaho baked potato...

11:20.346 --> 11:22.140
and a 2-inch steak.

11:22.140 --> 11:23.433
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:23.433 --> 11:24.976
<i>- When the steel</i>

11:24.976 --> 11:26.811
<i>takes on the color</i>
<i>of the sunset,</i>

11:26.811 --> 11:28.062
<i>that's when it's ready</i>
<i>to receive its soul.</i>

11:28.062 --> 11:30.273
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:30.273 --> 11:32.150
- Hey.
- Atsatsa with a nice,

11:32.150 --> 11:34.068
slow quench into the oil.

11:34.068 --> 11:36.946
<i>- The knife will</i>
<i>always receive the soul</i>

11:36.946 --> 11:39.240
<i>once it's quenched.</i>

11:39.240 --> 11:41.868
<i>All the work you've done</i>
<i>up to that point is finalized.</i>

11:41.868 --> 11:44.454
<i>You don't go back</i>
<i>from that part.</i>

11:44.454 --> 11:46.206
- 10 minutes, bladesmiths!

11:46.206 --> 11:47.790
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:47.790 --> 11:49.667
<i>- So I'm at this grinder,</i>

11:49.667 --> 11:52.921
<i>and I'm totally unfamiliar</i>
<i>with this machinery.</i>

11:52.921 --> 11:55.465
<i>The grinders are removing</i>
<i>a lot of material very fast,</i>

11:55.465 --> 11:58.092
and I'm not
accustomed to that.

11:58.092 --> 11:59.886
- I am a little bit worried
that Atsatsa

11:59.886 --> 12:03.014
has got those bevels
coming past that pinhole.

12:03.014 --> 12:05.058
Nothing's gonna
line up very well...

12:05.058 --> 12:06.517
because the sides
of the ricasso

12:06.517 --> 12:08.478
are just not
gonna be parallel.

12:08.478 --> 12:14.567
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:14.567 --> 12:16.569
- Whoa.
- Oh, yeah.

12:16.569 --> 12:19.113
<i>- I don't go completely in,</i>
<i>all the way,</i>

12:19.113 --> 12:23.368
<i>so the tang pretty much</i>
<i>remains unquenched,</i>

12:23.368 --> 12:25.286
<i>and that's what I want,</i>
<i>is the tang to remain</i>

12:25.286 --> 12:28.122
soft and strong
rather than brittle.

12:28.122 --> 12:30.708
- Ten, nine, eight...

12:30.708 --> 12:33.670
seven, six, five...

12:33.670 --> 12:37.840
four, three, two, one.

12:37.840 --> 12:39.342
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

12:39.342 --> 12:40.635
Drop your tools.

12:40.635 --> 12:42.512
This round is over.
- Whoo!

12:42.512 --> 12:44.430
I feel good about the blade.

12:44.430 --> 12:46.808
<i>The only question I have</i>
<i>is about that curved tang.</i>

12:46.808 --> 12:48.476
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:48.476 --> 12:50.311
- Bladesmiths,
now it's time

12:50.311 --> 12:52.563
for the judges to take
a closer look at your work.

12:52.563 --> 12:55.066
John, please present
your blade to the judges.

12:55.066 --> 12:57.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:57.652 --> 13:00.613
- My biggest concern
is your pivot hole.

13:00.613 --> 13:02.448
Now, that's the only connection

13:02.448 --> 13:04.993
this blade is gonna have
to your handle material.

13:04.993 --> 13:07.120
That's maybe 1/3 the size

13:07.120 --> 13:08.329
of the connection
you want for a pivot.

13:08.329 --> 13:10.248
It's just a weak spot,

13:10.248 --> 13:12.750
so I'd like to see you
do something to beef that up.

13:12.750 --> 13:13.793
- Thank you.

13:13.793 --> 13:15.336
- Bob, you're up.

13:15.336 --> 13:17.046
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:17.046 --> 13:19.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:19.090 --> 13:21.426
- I like the shape.
Very aggressive shape.

13:21.426 --> 13:23.636
I'm not sure
if I like the alignment

13:23.636 --> 13:25.179
of the tail, though.

13:25.179 --> 13:26.764
It's either gonna be

13:26.764 --> 13:29.267
an interesting
handle configuration,

13:29.267 --> 13:31.853
or this is gonna be high,
or the blade's gonna be low

13:31.853 --> 13:34.063
when it's opened
or closed, but...

13:34.063 --> 13:35.690
I like the beginnings
of this.

13:35.690 --> 13:37.150
- All right, Derek,

13:37.150 --> 13:38.609
please present your blade
to the judges.

13:38.609 --> 13:40.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:40.403 --> 13:42.280
<i>- I really do like</i>
<i>the shape of this</i>

13:42.280 --> 13:44.657
and the look of it,
but my brain's trying

13:44.657 --> 13:47.326
to figure how that curve
is gonna go over that straight.

13:47.326 --> 13:49.203
Now, I'm not sure
if you're designing this

13:49.203 --> 13:52.040
to sit on top of the handle
or to lay into the handle,

13:52.040 --> 13:54.625
but if it sits on top,
make sure that's comfortable

13:54.625 --> 13:56.669
and it's not
creating hot spots.

13:56.669 --> 13:58.963
- Atsatsa, please present
your blade to the judges.

13:58.963 --> 14:01.549
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:01.549 --> 14:04.469
<i>- Well, Atsatsa, I like</i>
<i>the overall profile of this.</i>

14:04.469 --> 14:06.888
One thing I do have
a problem with, though,

14:06.888 --> 14:11.100
is your ricasso is basically
matching your blade.

14:11.100 --> 14:13.352
<i>With a tapering like this</i>
<i>into a V shape,</i>

14:13.352 --> 14:15.354
<i>the handle scales</i>
<i>will also form a V shape,</i>

14:15.354 --> 14:16.856
<i>and the blade</i>
<i>won't have a straight section</i>

14:16.856 --> 14:18.274
to fold into.

14:18.274 --> 14:20.485
That ricasso,
tapered in that way,

14:20.485 --> 14:22.361
that's just gonna cause
a lot of problems.

14:22.361 --> 14:26.365
- Bladesmiths, the judges
have made a final decision.

14:26.365 --> 14:28.034
The bladesmith
leaving The Forge is...

14:28.034 --> 14:31.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:31.162 --> 14:35.500
Atsatsa, your blade
did not make the cut.

14:35.500 --> 14:37.710
David Baker's
gonna tell you why.

14:37.710 --> 14:40.171
- Atsatsa, you brought us
a classic blade shape,

14:40.171 --> 14:42.298
but unfortunately you fell into
a couple of the classic traps

14:42.298 --> 14:44.509
when making a friction folder.

14:44.509 --> 14:47.386
<i>The grinds of your bevels go</i>
<i>all the way into the ricasso,</i>

14:47.386 --> 14:49.680
<i>making a wedge shape,</i>
<i>and that's not gonna line up</i>

14:49.680 --> 14:52.308
in your handle very well
and be snug.

14:52.308 --> 14:54.352
If it's snug
when its closed,

14:54.352 --> 14:56.062
it's not gonna be snug
when it's open.

14:56.062 --> 14:57.522
We feel,
going into a second round,

14:57.522 --> 14:59.023
your blade has more work

14:59.023 --> 15:00.399
than any of the other smiths.

15:00.399 --> 15:02.777
That's why
we're letting you go.

15:02.777 --> 15:05.321
- Atsatsa,
please surrender your blade.

15:05.321 --> 15:07.865
<i>- I think the judges'</i>
<i>decision is very valid.</i>

15:07.865 --> 15:09.867
<i>So when I go home,</i>
<i>I'm definitely gonna focus</i>

15:09.867 --> 15:13.162
on getting a grinder
and just practice on that one.

15:13.162 --> 15:16.415
I'm feeling a bit down,
but I'm so stoked

15:16.415 --> 15:19.544
I was actually able to come
and be on "Forged in Fire"

15:19.544 --> 15:22.130
and just, like, compare myself
to these amazing bladesmiths.

15:22.130 --> 15:23.923
<i>And it definitely will be</i>
<i>something I remember</i>

15:23.923 --> 15:26.134
for a lifetime
and a great motivator

15:26.134 --> 15:27.385
and teacher.

15:27.385 --> 15:29.679
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:29.679 --> 15:31.931
- All right, bladesmiths.
Congratulations.

15:31.931 --> 15:34.350
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

15:34.350 --> 15:36.018
and now that your blades
have been tempered,

15:36.018 --> 15:37.854
it's time to turn them
into fully functioning

15:37.854 --> 15:40.398
friction folders
by attaching handles to them.

15:40.398 --> 15:42.775
You will have three hours
in which to complete your work,

15:42.775 --> 15:45.987
and when the time runs out,
your blades will be tested

15:45.987 --> 15:48.990
for strength and durability
in a brutal strength test--

15:48.990 --> 15:51.159
I'm still not gonna
tell you what it is--

15:51.159 --> 15:54.120
and for edge retention
in a sharpness test.

15:54.120 --> 15:55.955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:55.955 --> 15:57.290
Your friction folders,
at the end of this round,

15:57.290 --> 15:59.417
<i>must remain so</i>

15:59.417 --> 16:01.544
<i>without the addition</i>
<i>of any mechanical device.</i>

16:01.544 --> 16:04.463
<i>Friction has to hold</i>
<i>that blade in place.</i>

16:04.463 --> 16:05.673
Good luck, bladesmiths.

16:05.673 --> 16:08.092
Your three hours starts...

16:08.092 --> 16:09.385
now.

16:09.385 --> 16:11.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:11.846 --> 16:14.932
There's a lot
of really fine detail work

16:14.932 --> 16:16.893
that needs to be completed
in this round.

16:16.893 --> 16:18.978
What's the first thing
you're doing, J.?

16:18.978 --> 16:21.856
- First thing I'd be doing is
making a pattern for my handle.

16:21.856 --> 16:24.400
I'd be marking a pivot area
and make sure I'm gonna have

16:24.400 --> 16:27.403
enough handle to cover
the tip of the edge.

16:27.403 --> 16:29.197
- Man.
- I hear ya.

16:29.197 --> 16:30.907
I'm so confused.

16:30.907 --> 16:32.992
- What have
I gotten myself into?

16:32.992 --> 16:35.119
- I have no idea
what I'm doing, so...

16:35.119 --> 16:37.663
<i>There's so many things to do,</i>

16:37.663 --> 16:41.292
<i>and never having made</i>
<i>a friction folder before,</i>

16:41.292 --> 16:44.045
I'm thinking, "Oh, gosh, now
what am I gonna do about this?"

16:44.045 --> 16:45.713
Just not what I want.

16:45.713 --> 16:48.466
There's just
so much mental stress.

16:48.466 --> 16:50.092
- If they don't
figure out their design

16:50.092 --> 16:52.011
and nail it down now...

16:52.011 --> 16:54.305
they're in big trouble
the rest of the challenge.

16:54.305 --> 16:55.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:55.389 --> 16:57.183
<i>- My original intent was</i>

16:57.183 --> 16:59.435
I wanted something
a little fuller in the handle

16:59.435 --> 17:02.188
<i>but couldn't find</i>
<i>what I wanted.</i>

17:02.188 --> 17:05.358
<i>Then I had to go to</i>
<i>the thinner piece of micarta,</i>

17:05.358 --> 17:08.986
so it kind of changed
the feel of the handle

17:08.986 --> 17:11.822
that I had in my head
before I got started.

17:11.822 --> 17:13.532
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:13.532 --> 17:15.576
<i>- There are precise</i>
<i>pivot points</i>

17:15.576 --> 17:17.245
and points of motion

17:17.245 --> 17:18.871
<i>and measurements</i>
<i>that have to be taken</i>

17:18.871 --> 17:20.539
so that the blade
and the handle material

17:20.539 --> 17:22.208
<i>line up</i>

17:22.208 --> 17:24.085
as well as maintaining
its ability

17:24.085 --> 17:27.046
to stay closed when closed
and open when open.

17:27.046 --> 17:29.382
- All those edges need
to be rounded off

17:29.382 --> 17:31.217
so they're not
tearing into your hand.

17:31.217 --> 17:34.554
Wherever the spine sets in
needs a stop.

17:34.554 --> 17:37.431
- I'm presented with problems
from the get-go

17:37.431 --> 17:38.599
with this handle...

17:38.599 --> 17:40.434
I'm losing my mind.

17:40.434 --> 17:43.145
<i>Having a straight blade</i>
<i>and a curved tang.</i>

17:43.145 --> 17:46.274
- I love to see art
become function.

17:46.274 --> 17:48.526
If he's able to do that
with the way it looks, a seax,

17:48.526 --> 17:50.194
with that curved tail then...

17:50.194 --> 17:51.696
Whoo-whoo!
I mean, I'm excited about that.

17:51.696 --> 17:53.864
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:53.864 --> 17:55.533
<i>- My handle</i>
<i>is essentially two pieces</i>

17:55.533 --> 17:59.287
of rectangular micarta
sandwiched together.

17:59.287 --> 18:02.999
I wanna keep things simple
because when you go complicated

18:02.999 --> 18:07.378
you run the risk
of having complicated problems.

18:07.378 --> 18:10.006
- John's over here
fitting his scales together.

18:10.006 --> 18:11.757
Man, they are thin.

18:11.757 --> 18:14.760
- John's got all these
teeny, tiny thin pins.

18:14.760 --> 18:16.470
- And if we're gonna put
some shock

18:16.470 --> 18:18.514
and stress
on those blades,

18:18.514 --> 18:20.558
it's gonna travel all the way
back to that pin connection.

18:20.558 --> 18:25.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:25.271 --> 18:28.482
- Bladesmiths,
90 minutes has elapsed.

18:28.482 --> 18:30.901
That leaves you with
90 minutes remaining.

18:30.901 --> 18:32.278
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:32.278 --> 18:34.905
- 90 teeny, tiny
little minutes.

18:34.905 --> 18:36.115
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:36.115 --> 18:37.325
As if John's blade

18:37.325 --> 18:38.784
wasn't thin enough.

18:38.784 --> 18:40.119
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:40.119 --> 18:41.662
- I hope that he rounds that--

18:41.662 --> 18:43.623
the tip of it when it's closed,

18:43.623 --> 18:45.416
'cause when it's closed,
it's a shank.

18:45.416 --> 18:47.501
You open up, it's a knife.
You close, it's a shank.

18:47.501 --> 18:49.754
You can't have anything pointy
when you put your hands on it.

18:49.754 --> 18:52.465
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:52.465 --> 18:55.760
- Derek's getting rid
of that spiral on the sides.

18:55.760 --> 18:57.887
<i>- Eventually, I get it</i>
<i>to where it shuts,</i>

18:57.887 --> 19:00.931
but the tab,
it just is not gonna fit.

19:00.931 --> 19:02.141
Mm.

19:02.141 --> 19:03.517
The tang should be soft enough

19:03.517 --> 19:05.019
<i>for me to be able to attempt</i>

19:05.019 --> 19:06.604
hammering it at the vice.

19:06.604 --> 19:08.022
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:08.022 --> 19:09.774
- Oh, boy.

19:09.774 --> 19:11.400
<i>- I take a couple</i>
<i>of whacks at it,</i>

19:11.400 --> 19:14.111
and it does move,
just slightly,

19:14.111 --> 19:15.863
and I think
this is gonna be fine.

19:15.863 --> 19:17.156
- Holy cow.

19:17.156 --> 19:22.495
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:22.495 --> 19:25.331
all: Oh!

19:25.331 --> 19:29.001
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:29.001 --> 19:31.295
<i>- And the tab</i>
<i>just makes a loud ping.</i>

19:31.295 --> 19:34.632
<i>Goes flying across the floor.</i>
<i>My heart sinks.</i>

19:34.632 --> 19:37.927
- I hope that that brittleness
is not also in the blade.

19:37.927 --> 19:40.054
- That would be a problem.

19:40.054 --> 19:42.014
<i>- I realize really quickly,</i>

19:42.014 --> 19:43.599
<i>this is a great thing</i>
<i>that's happened.</i>

19:43.599 --> 19:46.352
I have a middle pin
already in place

19:46.352 --> 19:47.603
that's gonna act as a stop.

19:47.603 --> 19:50.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:50.564 --> 19:53.484
- Five, four, three,

19:53.484 --> 19:55.277
two, one.

19:55.277 --> 19:57.405
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

19:57.405 --> 19:59.240
This round is over.

19:59.240 --> 20:00.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:00.991 --> 20:02.868
<i>- I feel very confident</i>
<i>in my blade.</i>

20:02.868 --> 20:05.788
<i>I didn't go for looks,</i>
<i>I went for functionality,</i>

20:05.788 --> 20:08.249
but it works.

20:08.249 --> 20:09.959
- Bladesmiths...

20:09.959 --> 20:11.836
welcome to our strength test.

20:11.836 --> 20:13.921
The Bolt Baton.

20:13.921 --> 20:17.425
Now, what I'm gonna do
is take this well-used bat,

20:17.425 --> 20:19.260
and I'm gonna take
your friction folders,

20:19.260 --> 20:22.388
and I'm gonna baton
the back of your blades

20:22.388 --> 20:25.057
at three different points
on those bolts.

20:25.057 --> 20:28.102
<i>- I wasn't anticipating</i>
<i>such a brutal test.</i>

20:28.102 --> 20:29.770
I don't know why
I wouldn't think that.

20:29.770 --> 20:31.605
I mean, I've watched
"Forged in Fire."

20:31.605 --> 20:33.399
- Now, as far as what
your blades do to the bolts,

20:33.399 --> 20:34.942
I don't really care.

20:34.942 --> 20:36.444
What I wanna see
is what the bolts

20:36.444 --> 20:37.987
are gonna do to your blades.

20:37.987 --> 20:39.530
Derek, you're up first.
You ready?

20:39.530 --> 20:41.657
- Ugh.
Yeah, I guess.

20:41.657 --> 20:43.033
Do what you do.

20:43.033 --> 20:46.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:46.162 --> 20:48.748
<i>J. looks like</i>
<i>an evil villain</i>

20:48.748 --> 20:51.083
<i>ready to do</i>
<i>some serious destruction.</i>

20:51.083 --> 20:52.543
Come on, baby.

20:52.543 --> 20:54.003
Hold together.

20:54.003 --> 20:56.046
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

20:56.046 --> 20:57.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:57.715 --> 21:00.217
- [grunts]

21:00.217 --> 21:02.136
- Ugh.
[laughs]

21:02.136 --> 21:04.555
- It didn't fly apart.
- That's hard to watch.

21:04.555 --> 21:06.849
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:06.849 --> 21:08.851
- All right, Derek.
First of all,

21:08.851 --> 21:10.603
you do have a little bit
of edge damage here.

21:10.603 --> 21:11.979
You got a couple of rolls here

21:11.979 --> 21:13.773
where I can actually
catch my nail on.

21:13.773 --> 21:15.983
You do still have tension,
but the problem is...

21:15.983 --> 21:17.818
your blade did shift.

21:17.818 --> 21:18.986
- Okay.

21:18.986 --> 21:20.362
- And when I go to close it...

21:20.362 --> 21:23.240
now it's catching
on this side.

21:23.240 --> 21:24.533
But...

21:24.533 --> 21:26.869
your edge held up
fairly well.

21:26.869 --> 21:28.871
Overall, good job.
- Thank you.

21:28.871 --> 21:30.623
- Bob, you ready to play?

21:30.623 --> 21:33.334
- It's what I came for.
- All right, let's do it.

21:33.334 --> 21:35.503
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:35.503 --> 21:37.713
<i>- My edge profile might be</i>

21:37.713 --> 21:40.382
<i>just a little bit thin</i>
<i>for this test,</i>

21:40.382 --> 21:42.259
so I'm nervous

21:42.259 --> 21:44.970
as a long-tailed cat
in a room full of rockers.

21:44.970 --> 21:46.597
- You got this.

21:46.597 --> 21:48.140
- We'll see.

21:48.140 --> 21:50.684
- [grunting]

21:50.684 --> 21:53.729
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

21:53.729 --> 21:55.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:55.815 --> 21:59.026
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:59.026 --> 22:01.111
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:01.111 --> 22:05.282
All right, Bob.
The big issue...

22:05.282 --> 22:07.034
Was...
- Oh.

22:07.034 --> 22:09.203
- There's no mechanical
connection back here.

22:09.203 --> 22:10.913
There's no pins.

22:10.913 --> 22:12.498
When I struck the spine,

22:12.498 --> 22:14.792
the shock traveling
down that blade

22:14.792 --> 22:16.794
just blew that epoxy apart.

22:16.794 --> 22:19.630
So, on the blade,
good heat treat,

22:19.630 --> 22:22.466
good finish, good grinds,
very nicely done.

22:22.466 --> 22:24.009
Handle...
- Not so much.

22:24.009 --> 22:25.594
- Not so much.

22:25.594 --> 22:27.137
All right, John.
How you feeling?

22:27.137 --> 22:29.223
- Ugh...
Just ready to get it over with.

22:29.223 --> 22:31.517
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:31.517 --> 22:35.062
<i>Mine has got to be</i>
<i>the thinnest blade there.</i>

22:35.062 --> 22:38.649
It's not meant to have
this type of abuse put on it.

22:38.649 --> 22:39.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:39.650 --> 22:40.901
- Mm-hmm.

22:40.901 --> 22:42.862
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

22:42.862 --> 22:44.989
[grunting]

22:44.989 --> 22:48.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:48.158 --> 22:49.910
[grunts]

22:53.247 --> 22:55.207
<i>[tense music]</i>

22:55.207 --> 22:56.917
Mm, little blood this time.

22:56.917 --> 22:59.378
All right, John,
we got a few issues here.

22:59.378 --> 23:01.130
You don't have rolls
on your edge,

23:01.130 --> 23:03.591
<i>you have pieces missing,</i>

23:03.591 --> 23:06.427
and though I like the fact
that you used a steel pin,

23:06.427 --> 23:09.763
it's very small,
and it didn't hold.

23:09.763 --> 23:11.348
Just blew right out of place.

23:11.348 --> 23:13.851
So now your blade just...

23:13.851 --> 23:15.352
Your pivot point
just didn't hold up.

23:15.352 --> 23:20.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:20.941 --> 23:23.736
- To see and test
the edge of your folders,

23:23.736 --> 23:25.863
I'm gonna take your weapon
and slice across these hams.

23:25.863 --> 23:27.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:27.406 --> 23:28.866
Derek, you're up first.
You ready?

23:28.866 --> 23:30.492
- Yes, sir.

23:30.492 --> 23:33.537
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

23:33.537 --> 23:40.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:42.671 --> 23:45.633
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:45.633 --> 23:47.509
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.509 --> 23:49.136
- Let's talk about the edge.

23:49.136 --> 23:51.472
It's razor sharp.
- All right.

23:51.472 --> 23:53.599
- The way I was able
to cut through this ham,

23:53.599 --> 23:56.060
it sliced easily and deep.

23:56.060 --> 23:58.437
Your blade will cut.
- All right.

23:58.437 --> 24:00.189
- Good job.
- Thank you.

24:00.189 --> 24:01.774
- All right, Bob,
it's your turn.

24:01.774 --> 24:03.734
You ready?
- If you're ready, I'm willing.

24:03.734 --> 24:05.152
- Let's do this.

24:05.152 --> 24:08.072
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

24:08.072 --> 24:14.787
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:19.291 --> 24:20.960
- Very nice.

24:20.960 --> 24:24.463
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:24.463 --> 24:26.215
- All right, Bob.
We have an issue

24:26.215 --> 24:28.425
with your handle here
being loose,

24:28.425 --> 24:30.427
but the good thing
about friction folders is,

24:30.427 --> 24:33.055
it is the hand that holds it
in place with the handle,

24:33.055 --> 24:35.849
secure enough to where
I'm still able to test with it.

24:35.849 --> 24:37.977
I like the way
it feels in the hand.

24:37.977 --> 24:40.145
Your edge is sharp.

24:40.145 --> 24:42.648
It slices easy,
it's light and fast,

24:42.648 --> 24:44.108
and...

24:44.108 --> 24:45.776
it will cut.
- Thank you.

24:45.776 --> 24:47.444
- Good job.

24:47.444 --> 24:48.696
All right, John.
It's your turn.

24:48.696 --> 24:50.531
You ready?
- Let's do it.

24:50.531 --> 24:54.451
I am extremely nervous
about the chips on the blade,

24:54.451 --> 24:57.579
<i>and the blade</i>
<i>will no longer stay open.</i>

24:57.579 --> 24:59.498
<i>I'm really praying</i>
<i>right now</i>

24:59.498 --> 25:01.750
that Doug will be able
to still use it

25:01.750 --> 25:05.504
in the sharpness test.

25:05.504 --> 25:12.011
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:15.264 --> 25:17.474
- Nice.
Way to go.

25:17.474 --> 25:18.559
- Thank you.

25:18.559 --> 25:20.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:20.352 --> 25:21.854
- All right, John, let's talk
about your blade here.

25:21.854 --> 25:24.648
Despite having chips
on the edge here,

25:24.648 --> 25:27.484
as you can see,
it cuts easily into the ham.

25:27.484 --> 25:29.361
It's just this part where

25:29.361 --> 25:31.613
you can't keep it closed
without holding onto it.

25:31.613 --> 25:32.865
It's lost its friction
on that part.

25:32.865 --> 25:33.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:33.949 --> 25:35.325
It will cut.

25:35.325 --> 25:37.536
- Thank you, sir.
- Good job.

25:37.536 --> 25:39.830
- Bladesmiths,
the weapons tests are complete.

25:39.830 --> 25:42.541
So that the judges and I can
focus on the finer features

25:42.541 --> 25:44.918
of your "Forged in Fire" fully
functional friction folders,

25:44.918 --> 25:48.047
I'm gonna ask you to please
step off The Forge floor.

25:48.047 --> 25:51.216
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:51.216 --> 25:53.761
- That was brutal.

25:53.761 --> 25:55.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:55.471 --> 25:57.514
- That was...hard to watch.

25:57.514 --> 25:59.183
- Yeah.

25:59.183 --> 26:01.894
- So can we assume
that Derek is moving forward

26:01.894 --> 26:04.396
and just leave him out of this
portion of the deliberation?

26:04.396 --> 26:05.773
- It held up well.

26:05.773 --> 26:07.691
- All right,
let's start with

26:07.691 --> 26:09.193
John's blade right here.

26:09.193 --> 26:10.736
<i>- The big thing is that</i>

26:10.736 --> 26:12.654
<i>that pivot point broke loose.</i>

26:12.654 --> 26:14.031
<i>Small pin.</i>

26:14.031 --> 26:15.240
We warned him about that.

26:15.240 --> 26:16.575
He didn't listen.

26:16.575 --> 26:19.203
And then we've
got this problem.

26:19.203 --> 26:22.956
It is a vertical guillotine.

26:22.956 --> 26:25.334
And this sucker is sharp,

26:25.334 --> 26:27.377
and that's what came up
and bit me in the hand.

26:27.377 --> 26:30.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:30.464 --> 26:32.841
- What do we think
of Bob's blade?

26:32.841 --> 26:35.427
- Design-wise, it all fits
together really nicely.

26:35.427 --> 26:36.887
It's comfortable.

26:36.887 --> 26:38.847
When you look at
the area that split,

26:38.847 --> 26:40.599
when he squeezed that down,

26:40.599 --> 26:43.060
<i>he pushed all the glue</i>
<i>right to the edge,</i>

26:43.060 --> 26:44.228
and it just didn't bond.

26:44.228 --> 26:45.270
- I thought you actually did

26:45.270 --> 26:46.688
have a pin down in there.

26:46.688 --> 26:47.940
- Well, in the heat
of the battle,

26:47.940 --> 26:49.274
you just kind of forget things.

26:49.274 --> 26:51.527
- His handle may have failed,

26:51.527 --> 26:53.112
but it's not catastrophic,

26:53.112 --> 26:54.822
because the thing
about friction folders is,

26:54.822 --> 26:56.782
it's held in place by the hand.

26:56.782 --> 26:58.033
So it was usable to test.

26:58.033 --> 26:59.576
So it's a functional blade.

26:59.576 --> 27:01.495
- All right.

27:01.495 --> 27:03.872
Now it's time to talk about
the guy that's going home.

27:03.872 --> 27:05.207
Doug, have you made
your final decision?

27:05.207 --> 27:06.208
- Yes, I have.
- Dave?

27:06.208 --> 27:07.751
- Yeah.
- J.?

27:07.751 --> 27:10.379
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's go tell our smiths.

27:10.379 --> 27:12.965
Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete,

27:12.965 --> 27:15.384
and it's time for one of you
smiths to leave The Forge.

27:15.384 --> 27:18.137
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

27:18.137 --> 27:20.097
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:20.097 --> 27:21.557
John.

27:21.557 --> 27:23.058
Your blade
did not make the cut.

27:23.058 --> 27:24.476
J. Neilson's
gonna tell you why.

27:24.476 --> 27:25.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:25.978 --> 27:27.354
- Now, John,
I liked your concept,

27:27.354 --> 27:29.147
but that small pin being
unsecured

27:29.147 --> 27:31.775
and popping loose, it's
no longer a friction folder,

27:31.775 --> 27:33.360
and because of that,
you failed to fulfill

27:33.360 --> 27:34.820
the requirements
of the challenge,

27:34.820 --> 27:36.280
and that's why we're
sending you home.

27:36.280 --> 27:39.074
- Understood.

27:39.074 --> 27:41.159
- John, please surrender
your weapon.

27:41.159 --> 27:44.496
<i>- It is disappointing</i>
<i>to have to go home,</i>

27:44.496 --> 27:47.332
<i>but my blade</i>
<i>just came up short.</i>

27:47.332 --> 27:49.793
Being able to be in a room
with guys

27:49.793 --> 27:52.170
<i>who have been doing this</i>
<i>a lot longer than I have</i>

27:52.170 --> 27:54.214
<i>and the knowledge that</i>
<i>they've been sharing with me,</i>

27:54.214 --> 27:55.549
that's what I really enjoy.

27:55.549 --> 27:57.676
<i>I get to go home now,</i>

27:57.676 --> 27:59.678
make knives,
and lock up bad guys.

27:59.678 --> 28:04.725
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:04.725 --> 28:06.602
- Bob, Derek,
congratulations.

28:06.602 --> 28:08.854
You've made it to the final
round of this competition,

28:08.854 --> 28:10.564
which means that you're both
one step closer

28:10.564 --> 28:12.441
to the title
of "Forged in Fire" champion

28:12.441 --> 28:14.818
and that check for $10,000.

28:14.818 --> 28:16.069
Now, when you showed up here,
we asked you

28:16.069 --> 28:17.863
to make fully functional
friction folders

28:17.863 --> 28:20.699
with an eye turned towards
performance and design.

28:20.699 --> 28:23.744
Well, that was to set you up
for this final challenge,

28:23.744 --> 28:25.495
because we're sending you back
to your home forge

28:25.495 --> 28:28.582
to recreate an iconic weapon
from history,

28:28.582 --> 28:31.209
what I am calling
the hotrod of swords.

28:31.209 --> 28:32.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:32.544 --> 28:34.212
That weapon is...

28:34.212 --> 28:35.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:35.923 --> 28:37.299
The smallsword.

28:37.299 --> 28:39.301
- Oh, wow.

28:39.301 --> 28:41.261
- Holy crap.

28:41.261 --> 28:43.305
<i>- A combination of fashion</i>
<i>and function,</i>

28:43.305 --> 28:45.682
<i>the French smallsword</i>
<i>originated in the 18th century</i>

28:45.682 --> 28:47.267
<i>as an evolved version</i>
<i>of the rapier.</i>

28:47.267 --> 28:49.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:49.144 --> 28:51.271
<i>Featuring a razor sharp,</i>
<i>triangle-shaped blade</i>

28:51.271 --> 28:53.732
<i>and a decorative hilt,</i>
<i>the thin but deadly weapon</i>

28:53.732 --> 28:55.859
<i>allowed for swift</i>
<i>pinpoint thrusts</i>

28:55.859 --> 28:58.111
<i>that easily pierced through</i>
<i>the flesh of an opponent.</i>

28:58.111 --> 29:00.364
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:00.364 --> 29:02.449
<i>As swords on the battlefield</i>
<i>started becoming obsolete,</i>

29:02.449 --> 29:04.952
<i>the smallsword rose as</i>
<i>a symbol of rank and wealth,</i>

29:04.952 --> 29:08.080
<i>reserved for the deadly sport</i>
<i>of the duel.</i>

29:08.080 --> 29:10.707
<i>Today, the needle-like blade</i>
<i>can be frequently seen</i>

29:10.707 --> 29:13.585
<i>in the hit television show</i>
<i>"Game of Thrones,"</i>

29:13.585 --> 29:16.046
<i>where Arya Stark utilizes</i>
<i>its sharp, pointy tip</i>

29:16.046 --> 29:17.714
<i>to conquer her enemies.</i>

29:17.714 --> 29:18.757
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:18.757 --> 29:20.050
<i>Your handle must include</i>

29:20.050 --> 29:22.010
<i>a knuckle-bow, arms,</i>

29:22.010 --> 29:24.346
<i>rear quillion, and pommel.</i>

29:24.346 --> 29:25.681
The blade itself must be

29:25.681 --> 29:27.557
between 30 and 32 inches
in length,

29:27.557 --> 29:29.559
be tri-fullered, double-edged,

29:29.559 --> 29:31.853
and tapered to a needle point.

29:31.853 --> 29:33.689
- [whistles]
<i>One of my main goals</i>

29:33.689 --> 29:36.984
in coming to "Forged in Fire"
was to challenge myself,

29:36.984 --> 29:39.903
<i>and this final challenge is</i>
<i>definitely fitting that bill.</i>

29:39.903 --> 29:41.405
- You'll have five days
at your home forge

29:41.405 --> 29:43.115
to complete this challenge.

29:43.115 --> 29:44.199
After five days,
you will return

29:44.199 --> 29:45.534
and present your smallswords

29:45.534 --> 29:47.411
to our panel of expert judges,

29:47.411 --> 29:49.579
and only after they've put them
through the paces

29:49.579 --> 29:51.873
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:51.873 --> 29:54.418
and hand you that check
for 10 grand.

29:54.418 --> 29:55.711
Good luck, bladesmiths.

29:55.711 --> 29:57.212
We'll see you in five days.

29:57.212 --> 29:58.588
- Good luck.
- Good luck.

29:58.588 --> 30:01.591
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

30:01.591 --> 30:03.593
<i>Today, my goal</i>

30:03.593 --> 30:06.763
<i>is to get two billets</i>
<i>of Damascus made.</i>

30:06.763 --> 30:08.557
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:08.557 --> 30:10.559
<i>One billet for the sword,</i>

30:10.559 --> 30:14.354
<i>and one billet I'll be using</i>
<i>for the clamshell guard</i>

30:14.354 --> 30:16.148
<i>and the hand guard.</i>

30:16.148 --> 30:19.234
<i>Damascus is taking</i>

30:19.234 --> 30:22.487
<i>two or three dissimilar metals</i>

30:22.487 --> 30:24.197
and welding them together,

30:24.197 --> 30:25.991
<i>and you come up</i>
<i>with a pattern.</i>

30:25.991 --> 30:27.617
<i>My pattern</i>
<i>for the blade will be</i>

30:27.617 --> 30:31.121
<i>a 68-layer twist Damascus.</i>

30:31.121 --> 30:33.999
<i>I'm making my smallsword</i>
<i>out of Damascus</i>

30:33.999 --> 30:37.335
<i>because there needs to be</i>
<i>something that sets you apart,</i>

30:37.335 --> 30:40.297
<i>and Damascus,</i>
<i>it's all one-of-a-kind.</i>

30:40.297 --> 30:42.758
<i>You could be the same shape,</i>
<i>the same handle,</i>

30:42.758 --> 30:44.551
but each pattern
is gonna be different,

30:44.551 --> 30:48.638
so that, in itself,
makes it a one-of-a-kind knife.

30:48.638 --> 30:52.142
But before finishing my
smallsword with Damascus,

30:52.142 --> 30:54.352
<i>I'd like to try it</i>
<i>on this 5160,</i>

30:54.352 --> 30:57.064
<i>and then that way,</i>
<i>if the Damascus does blow up,</i>

30:57.064 --> 30:59.399
<i>fall apart,</i>
<i>at least I've got a Plan B</i>

30:59.399 --> 31:02.235
<i>partially started.</i>

31:02.235 --> 31:04.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:04.488 --> 31:06.073
<i>- So we're here</i>
<i>at my home forge</i>

31:06.073 --> 31:07.657
<i>in beautiful</i>
<i>Clinton, Mississippi,</i>

31:07.657 --> 31:09.409
<i>and I'm really excited</i>
<i>to get started.</i>

31:09.409 --> 31:12.829
<i>I'm using 5160 for the blade</i>
<i>of the sword.</i>

31:12.829 --> 31:15.248
<i>I'm going with what I know.</i>

31:15.248 --> 31:17.084
<i>I've been beating this sword</i>
<i>to death all day today</i>

31:17.084 --> 31:19.002
<i>under the power hammer</i>
<i>and at the anvil,</i>

31:19.002 --> 31:21.630
<i>and that builds up a whole lot</i>
<i>of stress in the steel.</i>

31:21.630 --> 31:23.590
<i>I notice a little bit</i>
<i>of a warp in the blade,</i>

31:23.590 --> 31:25.467
<i>and I think that's</i>
<i>because this sword</i>

31:25.467 --> 31:27.260
<i>is so long and thin.</i>

31:27.260 --> 31:29.096
<i>I'm gonna be fighting</i>
<i>these bends</i>

31:29.096 --> 31:30.680
<i>from start to finish.</i>

31:30.680 --> 31:37.020
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:37.020 --> 31:38.772
- There seems to be--

31:38.772 --> 31:40.899
might have a little bit
of a problem.

31:40.899 --> 31:44.861
In forging this, I've
developed a crack right here,

31:44.861 --> 31:47.405
and then I have
another one here.

31:47.405 --> 31:50.117
<i>Cracks appearing</i>
<i>in a Damascus sword</i>

31:50.117 --> 31:52.702
<i>could cause</i>
<i>a catastrophic failure.</i>

31:52.702 --> 31:55.247
So we're just gonna go with--

31:55.247 --> 31:58.125
and use the 5160 for the blade.

31:58.125 --> 32:01.670
I'm gonna have to go
to my Plan B blade.

32:01.670 --> 32:03.797
I'm not gonna be very happy

32:03.797 --> 32:07.384
<i>because my plan</i>
<i>was a Damascus blade.</i>

32:07.384 --> 32:10.095
But this blade is toast,

32:10.095 --> 32:12.097
<i>so I fired up the forge.</i>

32:12.097 --> 32:14.432
<i>I'm still gonna get</i>
<i>a sword turned in.</i>

32:14.432 --> 32:17.561
<i>- Today is the most critical</i>
<i>day in the process.</i>

32:17.561 --> 32:19.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:19.271 --> 32:20.814
<i>I'm gonna quench first</i>
<i>and then do</i>

32:20.814 --> 32:22.315
<i>some really careful</i>
<i>grinding after.</i>

32:22.315 --> 32:25.402
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:25.402 --> 32:29.489
Felt no cracks, zero pings.
Whoo!

32:29.489 --> 32:30.907
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:30.907 --> 32:33.243
So what I really want to do

32:33.243 --> 32:37.956
is--is make this guard
in as few pieces as possible.

32:37.956 --> 32:40.417
<i>I know I underestimated</i>

32:40.417 --> 32:43.795
<i>how complex the handle fit-up</i>
<i>is on this smallsword.</i>

32:43.795 --> 32:45.422
It's taken everything I've got.

32:45.422 --> 32:49.092
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:49.092 --> 32:51.303
<i>- Now that I've lost</i>
<i>my Damascus blade,</i>

32:51.303 --> 32:53.638
<i>I'm way behind.</i>

32:53.638 --> 32:54.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:54.931 --> 32:57.017
<i>I'm definitely not pleased</i>

32:57.017 --> 32:59.477
<i>by not turning in</i>
<i>a Damascus blade,</i>

32:59.477 --> 33:01.354
<i>because that's my style.</i>

33:01.354 --> 33:03.732
But turning in
a monosteel blade

33:03.732 --> 33:06.109
is better than turning in
no blade at all.

33:06.109 --> 33:08.695
We do have just a bit
of a bow here.

33:08.695 --> 33:10.322
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:10.322 --> 33:11.531
<i>But I think those</i>
<i>are all things</i>

33:11.531 --> 33:12.949
<i>that can be taken out.</i>

33:12.949 --> 33:15.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:15.202 --> 33:17.954
[metal clattering]

33:17.954 --> 33:22.334
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:22.334 --> 33:24.669
<i>- I'm baffled as to why</i>
<i>that blade broke.</i>

33:24.669 --> 33:27.214
<i>I'm hoping that my next</i>
<i>heat treatment</i>

33:27.214 --> 33:30.133
<i>is going to hold up,</i>
<i>but with my past failure,</i>

33:30.133 --> 33:31.927
<i>I have doubts.</i>

33:31.927 --> 33:33.637
I have to try
and figure this out

33:33.637 --> 33:35.972
<i>because I've only got</i>
<i>one more shot.</i>

33:35.972 --> 33:39.476
<i>What has taken me four days</i>
<i>to get to this point--</i>

33:39.476 --> 33:43.313
<i>I have just one more day</i>
<i>to turn in a weapon.</i>

33:43.313 --> 33:45.982
<i>[tense music]</i>

33:45.982 --> 33:48.860
<i>- Initially, I thought about</i>
<i>threading the entire pommel</i>

33:48.860 --> 33:52.072
and having the entire pommel
be the mechanical lock

33:52.072 --> 33:53.782
for the whole handle,

33:53.782 --> 33:55.700
but I've looked back
at some diagrams

33:55.700 --> 33:57.994
<i>that show a threaded nut</i>
<i>on the bottom,</i>

33:57.994 --> 33:59.663
<i>so I'm probably</i>
<i>just gonna have</i>

33:59.663 --> 34:01.581
<i>a smooth hole</i>
<i>through the pommel</i>

34:01.581 --> 34:05.126
<i>and thread the end of the tang</i>
<i>and put a nut on it.</i>

34:05.126 --> 34:06.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:06.586 --> 34:08.171
Yeah, I'm happy with it.

34:08.171 --> 34:11.299
I'm done!
I'm ready to see it perform.

34:11.299 --> 34:14.386
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:14.386 --> 34:16.680
- Bob, Derek,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:16.680 --> 34:18.390
You've had five days
at your home forges

34:18.390 --> 34:21.226
to work on your smallswords,
and they look fantastic.

34:21.226 --> 34:23.770
Bob, tell us a little bit
about your smallsword.

34:23.770 --> 34:25.355
- The blade that
I'm presenting today

34:25.355 --> 34:27.691
happens to be the third blade
that I made.

34:27.691 --> 34:29.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:29.442 --> 34:31.945
<i>The blade itself</i>
<i>is a 5160.</i>

34:31.945 --> 34:35.448
<i>Clamshell guard,</i>
<i>68-layer Damascus twist.</i>

34:35.448 --> 34:37.242
- All right.
Derek, how'd it go for you?

34:37.242 --> 34:38.493
- It was really challenging.

34:38.493 --> 34:40.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:40.161 --> 34:42.455
<i>My blade's made of 5160</i>
<i>spring steel.</i>

34:42.455 --> 34:44.291
<i>Clamshell guard</i>
<i>and knuckle-bow</i>

34:44.291 --> 34:46.167
<i>is really old wrought iron.</i>

34:46.167 --> 34:47.419
- All right, bladesmiths.

34:47.419 --> 34:48.837
Each of your blades will now be

34:48.837 --> 34:50.547
put through a series
of three tests.

34:50.547 --> 34:53.174
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

34:53.174 --> 34:55.427
and up first, the kill test.

34:55.427 --> 34:56.428
Doug?

34:56.428 --> 34:58.722
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:58.722 --> 34:59.973
- The smallsword.

34:59.973 --> 35:01.725
To see what kind
of lethal damage

35:01.725 --> 35:03.226
your weapons will do,
I will take your swords

35:03.226 --> 35:05.020
and deliver lethal cuts
and stabs

35:05.020 --> 35:06.688
on this ballistics dummy.

35:06.688 --> 35:08.607
All right, Derek.
Ready for this?

35:08.607 --> 35:10.233
- I think so.

35:10.233 --> 35:12.068
<i>I'm really looking forward</i>
<i>to see</i>

35:12.068 --> 35:14.696
how the blade performs,
but at the same time,

35:14.696 --> 35:16.781
<i>I'm nervous about the blade</i>
<i>catching in a rib</i>

35:16.781 --> 35:18.116
<i>and snapping.</i>

35:18.116 --> 35:19.534
Come on, baby.

35:19.534 --> 35:21.786
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:21.786 --> 35:24.372
My heart is in my throat
right now.

35:24.372 --> 35:27.375
<i>[rock music]</i>

35:27.375 --> 35:34.257
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:42.182 --> 35:44.017
[whispers]
Oh, my gosh.

35:46.311 --> 35:48.355
- All right, Derek, let's talk
about your blade right here.

35:48.355 --> 35:49.814
It is light.
It is pointy.

35:49.814 --> 35:51.191
It is sharp.

35:51.191 --> 35:53.068
Your weapon...will kill.

35:53.068 --> 35:55.111
- Thank you.
- Good job.

35:55.111 --> 35:57.364
Bob, it's quite something
to follow up with.

35:57.364 --> 35:59.574
You ready?
- That's what I came for.

35:59.574 --> 36:02.077
<i>My heart is just pounding.</i>

36:02.077 --> 36:03.953
I mean, I have confidence,
but...

36:03.953 --> 36:05.914
you don't really know, 'cause
I haven't done any tests.

36:05.914 --> 36:07.749
<i>I didn't even stab</i>
<i>a watermelon.</i>

36:07.749 --> 36:08.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:08.708 --> 36:11.753
<i>[rock music]</i>

36:11.753 --> 36:18.635
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:25.809 --> 36:26.768
- [whispers] Wow.

36:26.768 --> 36:28.895
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:28.895 --> 36:30.772
Nice work.
- Phew.

36:30.772 --> 36:31.981
- All right, Bob.

36:31.981 --> 36:33.900
The point is sharp enough

36:33.900 --> 36:36.236
to deliver a straight thrust
all the way through

36:36.236 --> 36:37.737
this ballistics dummy.

36:37.737 --> 36:39.447
Your weapon, sir...

36:39.447 --> 36:40.532
will kill.

36:40.532 --> 36:42.325
- Thank you.

36:42.325 --> 36:45.036
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:45.036 --> 36:46.955
- Bladesmiths, welcome
to our strength test:

36:46.955 --> 36:49.833
the flex test.

36:49.833 --> 36:52.127
Now, what I'm gonna do is take
each of your smallswords

36:52.127 --> 36:56.047
and bend them 45 degrees
in both directions.

36:56.047 --> 36:57.882
Now, if you nailed your
heat treat and construction,

36:57.882 --> 36:59.843
everything should stay true.

36:59.843 --> 37:01.219
How you feeling, Derek?
- Go ahead.

37:01.219 --> 37:02.470
- All right.

37:02.470 --> 37:09.185
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.031 --> 37:24.576
- [sighs]
- Stood up.

37:24.576 --> 37:28.705
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:28.705 --> 37:31.958
- Well, Derek,
I'm very impressed.

37:31.958 --> 37:35.879
This sucker went 45 degrees
both ways.

37:35.879 --> 37:37.547
Great job.

37:37.547 --> 37:38.673
- Thank you.

37:38.673 --> 37:40.592
- Bob, you ready?

37:40.592 --> 37:42.177
- Now I'm really worried.

37:42.177 --> 37:44.304
<i>I had to make this blade</i>
<i>in one day.</i>

37:44.304 --> 37:47.182
I had to get the heat treatment
all in the same day.

37:47.182 --> 37:50.226
My biggest fear
is that it's gonna break.

37:50.226 --> 37:53.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:53.897 --> 37:56.232
Now I'm really worried.

37:56.232 --> 37:57.984
I had to forge it out
in one day.

37:57.984 --> 38:00.487
I had to assemble it
all in the same day

38:00.487 --> 38:01.946
to get everything put together

38:01.946 --> 38:03.531
just so I could turn in
a sword.

38:03.531 --> 38:04.991
<i>I mean,</i>
<i>I'd already broken one,</i>

38:04.991 --> 38:07.869
<i>so I know it could be brittle.</i>

38:07.869 --> 38:10.830
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:10.830 --> 38:17.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:17.670 --> 38:20.423
<i>Each degree that it's going,</i>
<i>I'm going,</i>

38:20.423 --> 38:22.926
<i>"Is it gonna break here?</i>
<i>Is it gonna break here?"</i>

38:22.926 --> 38:25.637
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:25.637 --> 38:26.679
Agonizing.

38:26.679 --> 38:28.181
Okay, come back now.

38:28.181 --> 38:29.349
Then you go to the other side.

38:29.349 --> 38:36.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:52.455 --> 38:54.165
[exhales]

38:58.461 --> 39:01.631
- Well, Bob, good news
is your blade didn't break.

39:01.631 --> 39:03.216
- What a relief.

39:03.216 --> 39:05.635
- Didn't spring back to true,

39:05.635 --> 39:08.263
but it did come
most of the way back.

39:08.263 --> 39:09.848
Overall, nicely done.
- Thank you.

39:09.848 --> 39:11.599
- Okay, guys,
now is the sharpness test.

39:11.599 --> 39:12.976
Dave.

39:12.976 --> 39:15.562
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:15.562 --> 39:17.021
- All right, gentlemen.

39:17.021 --> 39:18.773
The smallsword
was specifically designed

39:18.773 --> 39:20.191
for civilian dueling,

39:20.191 --> 39:22.151
so to test the sharpness
of your weapon,

39:22.151 --> 39:23.736
I'll be doing multiple
harassing cuts

39:23.736 --> 39:25.822
to our sandman here.

39:25.822 --> 39:27.240
Derek, you're up first.
Are you ready?

39:27.240 --> 39:28.324
- Yeah, I guess so.

39:28.324 --> 39:30.118
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:30.118 --> 39:33.329
<i>[rock music]</i>

39:33.329 --> 39:38.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:41.045 --> 39:42.672
Right off,
when I picked this up...

39:42.672 --> 39:44.424
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:44.424 --> 39:47.343
That's a bit of an issue.

39:47.343 --> 39:49.137
- Okay.
- You know, every time it hit,

39:49.137 --> 39:52.473
it wanted to--
to roll in my hand.

39:52.473 --> 39:54.309
Other than
that slipping handle,

39:54.309 --> 39:55.393
it was quite a nice
weapon to use.

39:55.393 --> 39:56.686
- Good. Thank you.

39:56.686 --> 39:57.770
- All right, Bob, you're up.

39:57.770 --> 39:59.063
Are you ready?
- Yep.

39:59.063 --> 40:00.398
- Okay.

40:00.398 --> 40:01.941
<i>- I've never tried this,</i>

40:01.941 --> 40:03.651
<i>so I don't know</i>
<i>what's gonna happen.</i>

40:03.651 --> 40:06.696
<i>[rock music]</i>

40:06.696 --> 40:13.411
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:26.507 --> 40:28.801
- All right, first, Bob,

40:28.801 --> 40:30.511
not having the tip aligned,

40:30.511 --> 40:33.014
I'm not quite sure
where it's going to cut.

40:33.014 --> 40:34.891
But having that tip
two inches off

40:34.891 --> 40:36.434
where you think it's going
to be when you're--

40:36.434 --> 40:38.686
when you're trying to make
an accurate cut,

40:38.686 --> 40:40.563
uh, it's pretty tough.

40:40.563 --> 40:42.815
But your blade is sharp.

40:42.815 --> 40:44.651
Will definitely cut.

40:44.651 --> 40:45.568
It's just a little hard
to figure out

40:45.568 --> 40:46.861
where it's gonna cut.

40:46.861 --> 40:48.404
- Thank you.

40:48.404 --> 40:49.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:49.405 --> 40:50.907
- Bob, Derek,

40:50.907 --> 40:52.533
both of your finale weapons

40:52.533 --> 40:55.620
were strong, deadly,
and sharp.

40:55.620 --> 40:58.331
However, there can only be one
"Forged in Fire" champion,

40:58.331 --> 40:59.332
and that champion is...

40:59.332 --> 41:03.503
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:03.503 --> 41:04.545
Derek.

41:04.545 --> 41:06.047
Congratulations.

41:06.047 --> 41:08.049
You are the "Forged in Fire"
champion.

41:08.049 --> 41:10.009
Bob, unfortunately,
your smallsword

41:10.009 --> 41:12.387
did not make the cut.

41:12.387 --> 41:13.554
<i>- Bob, you made</i>
<i>a beautiful sword,</i>

41:13.554 --> 41:15.431
<i>but during that strength test,</i>

41:15.431 --> 41:17.016
<i>your blade took a bend</i>
<i>that set.</i>

41:17.016 --> 41:18.726
<i>It didn't straighten out,</i>

41:18.726 --> 41:20.186
and that's why we're
letting you go.

41:20.186 --> 41:22.230
- I understand.

41:22.230 --> 41:23.815
- Please surrender your blade.

41:23.815 --> 41:25.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:25.066 --> 41:26.401
<i>- Oh, I absolutely agree</i>

41:26.401 --> 41:28.111
<i>with the judges' decision</i>

41:28.111 --> 41:29.696
<i>that Derek did have</i>
<i>the better blade.</i>

41:29.696 --> 41:32.615
I may not be called
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:32.615 --> 41:35.076
but I gained so much more
valuable experience

41:35.076 --> 41:38.413
that...it's immeasurable.

41:38.413 --> 41:39.789
- Derek, congratulations.

41:39.789 --> 41:41.416
You are the "Forged in Fire"
champion,

41:41.416 --> 41:42.542
but this time,
we're gonna keep the money.

41:42.542 --> 41:44.585
What do you say?
- No.

41:44.585 --> 41:45.712
[laughter]

41:45.712 --> 41:47.296
- All right, Derek, please

41:47.296 --> 41:49.215
present your smallsword
to the judges.

41:49.215 --> 41:50.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:50.341 --> 41:51.718
<i>- It feels great!</i>

41:51.718 --> 41:52.677
I'm the "Forged in Fire"
champion.

41:52.677 --> 41:54.095
I can't believe it.

41:54.095 --> 41:55.930
<i>This entire competition</i>

41:55.930 --> 41:57.890
<i>has been personally</i>
<i>validating,</i>

41:57.890 --> 41:59.892
challenging,
inspirational.

41:59.892 --> 42:02.478
It's been just a lot of fun.

42:02.478 --> 42:04.772
And it might help me sell
a few blades as well.

42:04.772 --> 42:07.692
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

42:07.692 --> 42:12.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>
